Background:¶

Cardio Good Fitness is a retail store selling three different treadmills. We have been provided with customer data from previous purchases of these three treadmills.

Objective:¶

Create customer profiles for each product model by performing preliminary data analysis. Generate a set of insights and recommendations to help the company target new customers.

Data:¶

The data contains purchasing history for the various models

Product - the model no. of the treadmill Age - in no of years, of the customer Gender - of the customer Education - in no. of years, of the customer Marital Status - of the customer Usage - Avg. # times the customer wants to use the treadmill every week Fitness - Self rated fitness score of the customer (5 - very fit, 1 - very unfit) Income - of the customer Miles- expected to run

Observations of Dataset as a whole¶

  • The majority of customers range in age from 21 years old to 35 years old and are predominantly male
  • In relation to Education, if we assume 14 years of education equates to an Associates Degree and 16 years of education equates to a Bachelors degree, the largest clusters of customers form around those education levels. This suggests the majority of customers are college graduates with at least an Associates Degree.
  • The majority of customers planned on using the treadmill three to four times a week at time of purchase with most also assessing their fitness level at a mid-range of three.
  • The average annual income is approximately 53,000 USD, with the median of 50,500 USD and mode of 45,500 USD, suggesting income is somewhat skewed to due to some outliers with higher income.
  • The mean, median and mode of expected miles fluctuate in a range of 103 to 85. These figures are skewed to the left with outliers above the 200 mile range - this variable doesn't state the length of time for these figures-- are these expectations on a weekly basis as with usage? is that even significant?

Individual Product Analysis¶

  • In order to go into more indepth analysis of the individual products, first we must sort out the individual products and generate three smaller data sets
  • The three products are TM195, TM498 and TM798
  • While we don't have access to features and pricing of each individual product model, a quick analysis of income and age sorted by product suggests the TM195 is more of a budget model based on the income spread whereas the TM798 is more 'top of the line' based on the higher incomes of the customers. The TM498 appears to be the mid-range product.
In [332]:
sns.lmplot(x='Income',y='Age',data=fit,fit_reg=True,col='Product', hue='Gender')
plt.show()

Reviewing income in relation to age by individual products we see that for TM195 and TM498 the regression lines are almost identical, suggesting gender doesn't have that much impact on purchasing decisions. However, as income and age increase for the model TM798, more males tend to purchase the top of the line model than females.

Product TM195 Analysis¶

  • Equal numbers of male and female customers
  • More partnered than single customers by approximately one third
  • Median age of customer is 26, mean age is 28.5 and mode is 23, suggesting age data skewed to left. Fairly consistent bell shaped until male age 38 where there is a spike causing the skew
  • Usage seems to cluster around income ranging between 45,000 USD and 60,000 USD
  • Income not skewed as mean, median and mode are all approximate 46,000 USD
  • Expected usage 3-4 times a week regardless of other parameters
  • Average fitness level self assessed at between 2 and 3
  • Correlations are as would be expected - fitness level and mileage and usage as well as age, education and income
  • Expected usage seems to be higher and more consistent for partnered customers than single

Product TM498 Analysis¶

  • Fairly close distribution between male and female customers
  • More partnered than single customers by approximately one third
  • Median age of customer is 26, mean age is 28.9 and mode is 25, not quite as skewed as TM195, but skew caused by spike in female customers at age 33 and 40
  • mean and median income both close to 49,000 USD with mode being 45,500 USD
  • Usage appears to cluster around the income ranging between 45,000 USD and 55,000 USD
  • Expected usage is slightly lower peaking around 2.5 times per week
  • Fitness level self assessed at 3 more among partnered customers
  • Expected miles appear to top out around 170 with the exception of a few outliers
  • income peaks around 65,000 UDS with the exception of outliers
  • Correlations are as would be expected - fitness level and mileage and usage as well as age, education and income
  • Miles peaks more quickly for partnered than single customers

Product TM798 Analysis¶

  • Approximately 5 times more male than female customers
  • Partnered and single customers are more evenly distributed however there are still more partnered customers
  • Median age of customer is 27, mean is 29.1 and mode is 25, much less skewed than other two models
  • Mean and median income both around 75.000 USD wherase mode is much higher at 90,000 USD suggesting right skew - lowest income around 50,000 USD whereas with other models lowest income around 30,000 USD for TM195 and 35,000 USD for TM498
  • Usage is much higher for this model, most customers with a minimum of 4 times a week with majority ranging between 4-6
  • Self assessed fitness levels also higher with majority of customers rating themselves at 5
  • Other correlations as would be expected - fitness level and mileage and usage as well as age, education and income
